SIMPLE: uncouth
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Uncouth
<hw>Un*couth"</hw> <pr>(⟦ucr⟧n*k⟦oomac⟧th")</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<ety>[OE. <ets>uncouth</ets>, AS. <ets>unc⟦umac⟧⟦edh⟧</ets> unknown,
strange: <ets>un-</ets> (see <er>Un-</er> not) + <ets>c⟦umac⟧⟦edh⟧</ets>
known, p. p. of <ets>cunnan</ets> to know. See <er>Can</er> to be able,
and cf. <er>Unco</er>, <er>Unked</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Unknown.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧This <xex>uncouth</xex>
errand.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To leave the good that I had in hand,⟦br⟧
In hope of better that was <qex>uncouth</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Uncommon; rare; exquisite; elegant.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Harness . . . so <qex>uncouth</qex> and so rich.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Unfamiliar; strange; hence, mysterious; dreadful;
also, odd; awkward; boorish; <as>as, <ex>uncouth</ex>
manners</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Uncouth</xex> in guise and
gesture.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>I. Taylor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am surprised with an <qex>uncouth</qex> fear.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus sang the <qex>uncouth</qex> swain.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Awkward</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Un*couth"ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Un*couth"ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Uncovenable</ent>⟦br⟧
